A degree of combined leverage (DCL) is a <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/l/leverageratio.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">leverage ratio</a> that summarizes the combined effect that the <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="2" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/d/degreeofoperatingleverage.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">degree of operating leverage</a> (DOL) and the <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="3" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/d/dfl.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">degree of financial leverage</a> has on earnings per share (EPS), given a particular change in sales. This ratio can be used to help determine the most optimal level of financial and operating leverage to use in any firm.

